content.description: Surmount an opening section to a stance below a large pocket. A clean slab with a couple relatively small face holds at a slot eases into positive horizontals and a couple reachy pulls finishing under the roof.
content.protection: 4 bolts. Fixed steel lower off anchor.
content.location: This is the bolted line between Moon Compass and Thistle Do.

content.description: This worthy route seems to not get all that much attention due to the popularity of the routes at Burnside and the Refuge. Trolley or rock stack up to the starting jug and make a big move. Trundle through some slab and a couple hollow holds and execute an exciting crux to the ledge. Catch a great rest, then climb up and left from the last bolt through tafoni and traverse right toward the anchors.
content.location: Look for an obvious large hueco in the face, with a smaller pocket to the left. Maybe 20' left of the beginning of the horrible chossy undercut.

content.description: Starts in an obvious left-facing chalked flake. Follow a proud line of perfect incut crimps to a huge jump move to the jug pocket. Probably possible to top out but this one is generally done as a drop off.
content.protection: The landing kind of drops away on this one. Bring pads and a spotter or two.
content.location: Walking down toward the west end look for a perfect white and gray face with some obvious chalked crimps- three small holds and a juggy starting flake. The start flake is easily identified as the largest hold on the problem and has a small triangular protrusion. The climb is maybe 30 feet right of 1976.

content.description: Float up the low-angle face on comfy crimps and awesome ledges, finishing below the roof.

climbs.name: Thistle Don't
climbs.fa: Kevin jarvis, Carl Carter, Zach Wilhoit

content.description: Just right of Thistle, work up blank slab face towards curved cut in roof. Muscle over roof to the chains.

climbs.name: Thats not how you eat a banana
climbs.fa: Kevin jarvis, Carl Carter, Zach Wilhoit

content.description: Just left of tree, stretchy first move to easier climbing to chains.
Fun low crux with several solutions leads to easier terrain working towards an attention-getting finish to the lip.
content.location: Just left of 1976, and 20ish feet right of Thistle Do.

content.description: A powerful V4 boulder problem leads to a pair of pockets on the face. Super ultra thin and sloping crimps take you to a rad, incut pocket and a big dyno to the anchor. This route cuts off before the choss band above it, which would likely decrease the quality of the route. It is possible the extension may be bolted in the future. The grade is a guess, it could be a bit easier or way harder.
content.location: Continuing past Moon Compass and the other shorties, walk past the green arete and a tall undercut. The left side of the undercut has a big jug. Start here, heading slightly right then straight up.

climbs.name: Quarantina Turner
climbs.fa: Carl Carter, Kevin jarvis, Zach Wilhoit

content.description: Right side of tree. First clip is high; recommended stick clip. V3 start moves to easier climbing to chains.null

Starting off a rockstack, head up on a couple of jugs and then left on pockets to a huge move. Could be 5.11, could be a bit harder. If you're feeling really saucy, a direct start would certainly up the difficulty.
content.location: Continuing past Moon Compass, this is the 1-bolt route just before the gorgeous green arete.

content.description: A plethora of jugs, edges, and pockets leads to a thin 2-move crux. Bash enormous jugs to the anchors.
Start on the rising, under-cling rail. A handful of strenuous moves to the second bolt comprise the crux.
content.protection: 5 bolts, lower off anchor, stickclip recommended.
content.location: Travelling west, this is the first bolted line past the Zig-Zag area.

content.description: A V6 boulder problem leads to nice ledgey steep terrain, pull through the boulder problem and climb at mid 5.11
Thin faced climbing to mantle. Tall people might be able to clip chains from ledge.
Climb neat jugs and ledges to a break in the rock. A hard, fngery move gets you through the blank section. Top out on the dirty ledge to clip the anchors.
content.location: At the far West (clibmer's left) end; just right of Forgot My Crashpad.

content.description: Far left route. Blunted arete with 3 bolts up to anchors on a ledge (anchor carabiners hanging over lip on slings).
content.location: Far left route (as of 03/2017), just left of Ibexercise.

content.description: The furthest walls, some shorter routes on mostly nice stone. "Forgot the Crashpad" is the furthest left route.
